---
import "reveal.js/dist/reveal.css";
import "reveal.js/dist/theme/white.css";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Commercial auto risk scoring case study"
    />
    <title>Commercial Auto Risk Scoring</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="slides">
        <section class="title-slide">
          <p class="eyebrow">Applied AI / ML Data Scientist case study</p>
          <h1>Commercial auto<br />risk scoring</h1>
          <p class="muted">Peter Muzslay | July 2026</p>
          <p class="repo-link">
            <a
              href="https://github.com/peter115342/Data-Scientist-Applied-AI-ML-Case-Study"
              >github.com/peter115342/Data-Scientist-Applied-AI-ML-Case-Study</a
            >
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">1 | Business objective</p>
          <h2>Support commercial-auto underwriting</h2>
          <div class="two-column">
            <div>
              <h3>Decision</h3>
              <p>
                Estimate each policy line's probability of at least one claim,
                to support consistent risk assessment.
              </p>
              <h3>Target</h3>
              <p><code>claim_count &gt; 0</code> during the policy period.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3>Data</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>15,000 unique labelled policies from 2020-2022</li>
                <li>3,000 unlabelled policies from 2023-2024</li>
                <li>APD and AL coverage lines</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">2 | Starting point</p>
          <h2>What the supplied prototype did</h2>
          <div class="two-column">
            <div class="callout bad">
              <h3>Method issues</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Random split for a future scoring problem</li>
                <li>Independent category codes in train and score</li>
                <li>All missing values filled with zero</li>
                <li>Training-set accuracy presented as performance</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="callout bad">
              <h3>Leakage and output issues</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Current-period claim fields were included as predictors</li>
                <li>
                  Late-payment behaviour was used despite point-in-time risk
                </li>
                <li>Hard class labels were written instead of probabilities</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">3 | EDA and data quality</p>
          <h2>Analysis informed the improvements</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Claim rates differ by coverage and business type.</li>
            <li>External risk score is related to claim rate.</li>
            <li>Fleet, mileage, loss, and premium fields are skewed.</li>
            <li>
              Data-quality checks found duplicated policies, missing values, and
              invalid premiums.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="chart-grid">
            <img
              src="/figures/eda-claim-rates.png"
              alt="Claim rate by coverage and business type"
            />
            <img
              src="/figures/eda-risk-score-bands.png"
              alt="Claim rate by external risk score band"
            />
            <img
              src="/figures/eda-numeric-correlations.png"
              alt="Numeric feature correlations with the claim target"
            />
            <img
              src="/figures/eda-train-score-risk-distribution.png"
              alt="External risk score distribution in training and scoring data"
            />
          </div>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">5 | Improvement: point-in-time features</p>
          <h2>Removing information unavailable at underwriting</h2>
          <div class="two-column">
            <div class="callout good">
              <h3>Kept</h3>
              <p>
                Fleet, driver, prior-claims, premium, coverage, geography,
                payment frequency, and external-risk information.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="callout bad">
              <h3>Excluded</h3>
              <p>
                Current-period claim dates, paid amounts, claim status, days to
                claim, and late-payment count.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="muted small">
            The data dictionary explicitly marks current-period claim fields as
            only available after claim resolution.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">6 | Improvement: temporal validation</p>
          <h2>Testing on the future, not a random holdout</h2>
          <div class="timeline">
            <div><strong>2020</strong><span>Model selection</span></div>
            <div><strong>2021</strong><span>Validation and C tuning</span></div>
            <div><strong>2022</strong><span>Untouched test set</span></div>
            <div><strong>2023-24</strong><span>Score new policies</span></div>
          </div>
          <p>
            Six regularization strengths were compared on 2021 ROC-AUC. The
            selected logistic-regression setting was <code>C = 0.01</code>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">7 | Improvement: robust model pipeline</p>
          <h2>Making preprocessing consistent and safe</h2>
          <div class="three-column">
            <div>
              <h3>Numeric</h3><p>
                Median imputation, missingness indicators, standard scaling, and
                log transforms for skewed variables.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3>Categorical</h3><p>
                Most-frequent imputation and one-hot encoding with
                unknown-category handling.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3>Records</h3><p>
                75 duplicate policy records removed after consistency checks;
                invalid premiums treated as missing.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="muted small">
            Final estimator: regularized logistic regression - interpretable and
            suitable as a strong baseline.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">8 | Results</p>
          <h2>Held-out 2022 performance</h2>
          <div class="metric-row">
            <div class="metric"><strong>0.679</strong><span>ROC-AUC</span></div>
            <div class="metric">
              <strong>0.231</strong><span>Average precision</span>
            </div>
            <div class="metric">
              <strong>0.105</strong><span>Brier score</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="two-column compact">
            <div><strong>AL</strong><br />ROC-AUC 0.660 | claim rate 9.4%</div>
            <div>
              <strong>APD</strong><br />ROC-AUC 0.657 | claim rate 15.9%
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="muted small">
            Probability ranking and calibration are both reported; metrics are
            also broken out by coverage.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">9 | Learning curve</p>
          <h2>The model benefits from more history</h2>
          <figure class="learning-curve-card">
            <img
              src="/figures/temporal-learning-curve.png"
              alt="Training and validation ROC-AUC by cumulative 2020 training rows"
            />
          </figure>
          <p>
            The training-validation gap narrows as data increases. Validation
            performance plateaus near 0.66, so there is no strong sign of
            overfitting.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">10 | Improvement: production safeguards</p>
          <h2>Making scoring repeatable and traceable</h2>
          <div class="three-column">
            <div>
              <h3>Input contract</h3><p>
                Required-column and date checks fail early with clear messages.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3>Category fallback</h3><p>
                60 unseen scoring <em>rideshare</em> values map to <code
                  >other</code
                > and are recorded in metadata.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3>Outputs</h3><p>
                The fitted model, metrics, configuration, and one non-null risk
                score per policy are persisted.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">11 | Improvement: monitoring</p>
          <h2>Detecting input shift before outcomes arrive</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Numeric features: Population Stability Index (PSI) plus
              missingness rates.
            </li>
            <li>
              Categorical features: distribution distance and unseen values.
            </li>
            <li>PSI alert threshold: 0.25.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="callout good">
            Current 2023-2024 scoring data: no numeric PSI alerts.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">12 | Databricks delivery</p>
          <h2>Runnable from the Databricks Git folder</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Both the scorer and EDA use Databricks notebook source format.
            </li>
            <li>
              Both notebooks generate a requirements file from the pinned <code
                >pyproject.toml</code
              > dependencies, then install it with <code>%uv pip</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
              The project is available as a Databricks Git folder, so the same
              version-controlled files can be run there.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <img
            class="databricks-screenshot"
            src="/figures/databricks_risk_scorer.png"
            alt="Risk scorer running from the Databricks Git folder on serverless compute"
          />
        </section>

        <section>
          <p class="eyebrow">14 | Production roadmap</p>
          <h2>What remains before being production-ready</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>
              Governed ingestion, scheduled scoring, and data-quality ownership.
            </li>
            <li>Model registry, automated tests, approvals, and rollback.</li>
            <li>
              Outcome-based monitoring for drift, calibration, and coverage
              performance.
            </li>
            <li>
              Underwriting thresholds, human review, fairness analysis, and
              business-value measurement.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p class="muted small">
            Limitation: this model predicts claim occurrence, not severity or
            total loss cost.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="title-slide">
          <p class="eyebrow">15 | Close</p>
          <h2>Key takeaway</h2>
          <p class="subtitle">
            The prototype became a leakage-aware, time-validated probability
            scorer with repeatable preprocessing, meaningful evaluation, and
            production safeguards.
          </p>
          <p class="learning-outcomes">
            What I learned: temporal validation, calibration, and drift
            monitoring.
          </p>
          <hr />
          <p class="small muted">
            AI disclosure: I used GPT-5.6 Terra from OpenAI to brainstorm,
            review implementation choices, generate presentation code, and help
            explain results. I reviewed the approach and verified all changes
            and results.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>

    <script>
      import Reveal from "reveal.js";

      const deck = new Reveal({
        controls: true,
        hash: true,
        progress: true,
        slideNumber: "c/t",
        transition: "fade",
      });
      deck.initialize();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>

<style is:global>
  :root {
    --accent: #007f73;
    --ink: #172b3a;
    --muted: #526777;
    --panel: #eef7f5;
    --line: #c8d9d5;
  }

  body,
  .reveal-viewport {
    background: #fbfcfd;
  }
  .reveal {
    font-family: Inter, Aptos, Arial, sans-serif;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: 32px;
  }
  .reveal h1,
  .reveal h2,
  .reveal h3 {
    color: var(--ink);
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    text-transform: none;
  }
  .reveal h1 {
    font-size: 2.05em;
  }
  .reveal h2 {
    font-size: 1.4em;
  }
  .reveal h3 {
    font-size: 0.72em;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .reveal p,
  .reveal li {
    font-size: 0.68em;
    line-height: 1.35;
  }
  .reveal li {
    margin: 0.35em 0;
  }
  .reveal code {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .reveal .progress {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .title-slide {
    text-align: left;
  }
  .eyebrow {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.42em !important;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .subtitle {
    font-size: 0.78em !important;
    max-width: 25em;
  }
  .muted {
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .small {
    font-size: 0.44em !important;
  }
  .reveal p.muted.small {
    color: #2c4753;
    font-size: 0.54em !important;
  }
  .repo-link a {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.62em;
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .learning-outcomes {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.58em !important;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .two-column,
  .three-column,
  .figure-grid,
  .metric-row {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.7em;
  }
  .two-column {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }
  .three-column {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }
  .compact {
    margin-top: 0.7em;
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 0.61em;
  }
  .callout,
  .metric,
  .three-column > div,
  .figure-slot {
    background: var(--panel);
    border-radius: 0.35em;
    padding: 0.55em 0.65em;
  }
  .callout {
    margin-top: 0.6em;
  }
  .good {
    border-left: 5px solid var(--accent);
  }
  .bad {
    border-left: 5px solid #ca5d5d;
    background: #fff4f3;
  }
  .figure-grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    margin-top: 0.6em;
  }
  .chart-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 0.35em;
  }
  .chart-grid img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 10.2em;
    object-fit: contain;
  }
  .figure-card {
    margin: 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 0.35em;
    padding: 0.3em;
    background: #fff;
  }
  .figure-card img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 5.6em;
    object-fit: contain;
  }
  .figure-card figcaption {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.36em;
    margin-top: 0.35em;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .learning-curve-card {
    margin: 0.55em 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 0.35em;
    padding: 0.3em;
    background: #fff;
  }
  .learning-curve-card img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 12.5em;
    object-fit: contain;
  }
  .databricks-screenshot {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 16em;
    object-fit: contain;
  }
  .figure-slot {
    min-height: 3.2em;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    text-align: center;
    border: 1px dashed #86aaa2;
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .figure-slot strong {
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: 0.62em;
  }
  .figure-slot span,
  .figure-slot small {
    font-size: 0.42em;
    margin-top: 0.22em;
  }
  .learning-curve {
    min-height: 7em;
    margin: 0.7em 0;
  }
  .timeline {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 0.3em;
    margin: 0.8em 0;
  }
  .timeline div {
    border-top: 3px solid var(--accent);
    padding-top: 0.4em;
  }
  .timeline strong,
  .timeline span {
    display: block;
  }
  .timeline strong {
    font-size: 0.67em;
  }
  .timeline span {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.4em;
  }
  .metric-row {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    margin: 0.6em 0;
  }
  .metric {
    text-align: center;
  }
  .metric strong,
  .metric span {
    display: block;
  }
  .metric strong {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 1.2em;
  }
  .metric span {
    font-size: 0.42em;
    color: var(--muted);
  }
</style>
